segments.text: Would you care to evaluate council's support of you in that situation and why you think they acted as they did?
Well, I think that most members of council are generally not as strong-willed as I am.
And a number of them are more tolerant of disorderliness than I am and expressed to me the fact that they were very willing to proceed with that council meeting in a very disorderly environment.
That would be the case under any circumstances.
I've seen some of the same ones proceed in annexation hearings where there was a great amount of disorder, and it's just a difference of opinion.
What do you think the role of a city is when it comes to annexation and the rights of a city that doesn't want to be annexed?
Well, we don't annex other cities.
Each city has its own powers, and one city cannot annex another one.
We only annex areas in our extraterritorial jurisdiction that are unincorporated.
And I think our role is well defined by state law that we are required to prepare service plans to assure that the area that we're going to annex will be provided with adequate city services.
We're required to hold public hearings in the area to be annexed to explain those service plans.
And that is what we comply with.
At what point do you think Houston will stop annexing?
At the point when we stop growing, which I hope will not happen because the growth of the city has been good for the people who live here.
And so I do not see annexation as a finite kind of situation.
So then, by definition, annexation would be good for the people who annexed also?
Yes.
I think that...

The fact that Texas annexation laws provide for a city to expand its city limits to include the population base so that all of the population base shares one tax base and one service base have been very good and have kept us from suffering from the problems of other cities, particularly in the Northeast, in which the
the people or the taxpayers and the wealth has all left the inner city and gone into suburban cities and left the inner city with a deteriorating tax base that couldn't support itself.
Finally, the Houston Oilers have done a good job of ruining the city's image.
What do you plan on doing about the Houston Oilers?
Are they working against your administration?
Are they trying to ruin things for you?
What do you see as solving the problem?
If they run off Roe Campbell, I'll think that they're working against this administration.
But I thought the best way we could solve the problem was by having a successful team at the University of Houston.
However, other than the basketball team, we haven't managed to accomplish that as yet.
But we'll wait until next year.
We will then.
Wait until next year.
Thank you very much.
Okay.
Thank you.
